body:
> Take a reference from `receiver-otel`, you should add `enabledRules` for meter receiver. Because we have to activate meter-receiver in default

@wu-sheng 

Do you mean add config like this?

```yaml
receiver-otel:
  selector: ${SW_OTEL_RECEIVER:-}
  default:
    enabledHandlers: ${SW_OTEL_RECEIVER_ENABLED_HANDLERS:"oc"}
    enabledOcRules: ${SW_OTEL_RECEIVER_ENABLED_OC_RULES:"istio-controlplane"}

receiver-jvm:
  selector: ${SW_RECEIVER_JVM:default}
  default:
    enabledRules: ${SW_RECEIVER_JVM_ENABLED_RULES:"jvm"}
```

Now I have hard-coded the folder and file name
```java
 List<Rule> rules = Rules.loadRules("meter-analyzer-config", Collections.singletonList("jvm"));
 this.metricConverts = rules.stream()
                .map(it -> new MetricConvert(it, moduleManager.find(CoreModule.NAME).provider().getService(MeterSystem.class)))
                .collect(Collectors.toList());
metricConverts.forEach(metricConvert -> metricConvert.toMeter(jvmSampleFamilies));
```

> `meter-analyzer-config` is managed by `agent-analyzer` module's `meterAnalyzerActiveFiles` config. You should rely on that. And we need to disable `spring-sleuth`, but activate `jvm`. You don't need to hardcode.

@wu-sheng  `meterAnalyzerActiveFiles`  is used for MeterReceiver. If we want to use this configuration, we need to use the MeterReceiver protocol to accept jvm data.  Now if we use jvm receiver, we can only load the rules manually, and create metricConverts by rules  to handle it.

You can look at this class `JVMSourceDispatcher.java`.  Now it is manually parsed into jvmSampleFamilies data.

```java
 this.metricConverts = rules.stream()
                .map(it -> new MetricConvert(it, moduleManager.find(CoreModule.NAME).provider().getService(MeterSystem.class)))
                .collect(Collectors.toList());
metricConverts.forEach(metricConvert -> metricConvert.toMeter(jvmSampleFamilies));
```
